messages.text: DevOPs stands for development operations. It is the process of combining the talents of developers and operations to ensure often deployment and tailoring to product data
Dev-Ops is the process of taking a product from a development environment and turning it into a production product.
The cloud and deployment side of software, often including AWS services, etc.
DevOPs: Operations team of the development division at a company that focuses on maintaining existing codebases and ensuring QA.
DevOps: The process and technologies involved in deploying applications while maximizing security, availability, communications between services, and performance.
DevOPs is web developer and web operations integrated together to make sure the app or program is ready for deployment
Devops: is a way of programming software that establishes a close relationship between the developers and the Operations team.

<!channel> *Important.  Burn after reading.*

10 people were missing at stand-up and 7 missing at stand-down.  If this is the product of my being understanding about working from home, then I have erred because this is not the intended consequence.

*Attendance is still being taken at every stand-down and stand-up and both are mandatory*.  Though I have an understanding view _(i.e. one or two "sick" days)_, officially, there are no “work from home" days — else someone has to answer to state regulators.  Seriously, we each have to meet state guidelines regarding mandatory attendance _(Right?  I didn't know that there was such a thing either)_ — and we HAVE to meet them. Too many absences will hurt both you and me _(well, more you than me, but that's the sort of shit my father would say to me and I have no one else to say that shit to, except you guys, so nyah!)_

Of special interest is unexcused absences.  Unexcused absences are still recorded as such, and these are *very* limited.  “Working on Capstone” does not count as an excuse, same as “Working on Project for Deadline” is not a valid excuse at other workplaces.  As such, the answer to _"Should I stay home or go to campus”_ is _*"Go to campus”*_.

We are in the final stretch.  Come in, let’s work together, and take up all the conference rooms, and rock these last two and a half weeks.

then instead of running ```$ npm start``` to start up your server, run ```$ forever start bin/www``` where `bin/www` is your server file. in my case it actually is `app.js` so I've substituted in that. 
If you make changes to your backend and need to restart your server, run ```$ forever restart bin/www``` In my case I've placed both scripts in my package.json scripts under `forever` and `again`. This allows me to instead start my server with ```$ npm run forever``` and restart it with ```$ npm run again``` . I've also placed `forever stopall` under `stop` in my package.json scripts so that I can run ```$ npm run stop``` when I just need everything to stop for whatever reason.
to get it running you'll need to do ```$ sudo npm install -g forever``` on your instance's command line. (Any time you want to globally install a packed you need to `sudo` first.

messages.text: We can talk more tomorrow, but the tl;dr is you want to decompose the project into useful features, and ask your stakeholder to help you prioritize them. <@U1US8155M> is literally certified in doing that, btw.
So what would you do as one guy getting ready to eat an elephant? What would be your plan for something like this?
Both of you are trying to discover the best solution
And that's a _good_ thing
Because the reality is that they won't want the same thing in 6 months. When they use it one month in, they'll want to drop half the features and add 30 more
If you're doing agile, there's no 6 month MVP. every single iteration generates something of standalone value.

My thought, very likely erroneous, is that at some point within 6 months I will hit what they're initially thinking is an MVP. Then moving forward we can continue sprints a week or two at a time until they aren't really seeing much value added.
If they get sick of your shit (or you get sick of theirs), you can walk away with reasonable money, they walk away with useful software
This sounds like a BIG job. If you're looking to hire developers...I'm looking for a job...just saying
Agile relationships are built on trust. You're not locking them into a big commitment, they're not nailing you to the wall on scope
Do your estimates one iteration at a time
There's no such thing as estimating how many points a 6 month project will take
Eek. I don't understand much
Part of that is that you need to establish a velocity, not commit to the future, and not estimate anything you don't understand
But!
I'm a _huge_ fan of point billing
"Oh you meant that you need that? No problem I can throw that on. It's like another 3 points to get that done so we can do it for $1200"
I mainly like the idea of value points because I pay for my screw ups in estimating work, and they pay for their screw ups in communicating needs.
That hasn't been my experience.
Every freelancer in the world will tell you to charge hourly

I do worry about the unknown unknowns. Also they don't know what they're talking about. Clients often don't. But they also didn't lay out these requirements in that way. They actually said "hey, here's a WeWork login. How much and how long would it take you to do what they did?" This made me think, well they probably had teams of people build this over a very long time and teams of people iterating it as we speak. There's a million things going on here. But I have a renewed perspective on the amount of work that can be done in 6 months after going through this program.
Also I'm a little worried about an hourly rate. While on its face it seems a straightforward method of handling unknowns, I worry that it misaligns our incentives as a client and provider. I worry that the relationship to what could become almost half of my business might sour to something adversarial.

* Anyone asking for all those apps in _one_ probably doesn't know what they're talking about
* Galvanize has many seperate apps, but you can use the same login for all of them using their OAuth server
* They need to prioritize which apps they need the most, there's no way all of those could be built in 6 months
* Points mean nothing until you've done actual work. You estimate early, then update your estimates after you do some actual work. Way too many unknown unknowns.

What Chad said. If you commit to a flat fee, what recourse do you have if it goes over or they had their requirements wrong (which they have) or they argue for an "obvious" feature that they didn't state but argue was implicit?
Try to get them in on the “agile” method so they can change things as they go too

In my experience, projects never go as planned. With a project this big, I’d recommend you get an hourly rate established, estimate what you can but work on an hourly basis instead cause it WILL go over and you will be the one who takes the hit
It never is. That was a ballpark. What are you thinking?
That's assuming that it is only the 125 points. Is that with absolutely everything taken into account?

<@U2G2X2UQ1> <@U1X2N7XAM> <@U1US8155M> <@U1USJGEG2> <@U2WBQ64BY>

any freelancing in your pasts? I'm thinking 6 months $50k. Really I'm thinking 125 or so points. $400 a point. A point being normalized to what I should be able to accomplish in a day. And making sure that no story is too big to tackle in 3 days.
big project

I guess there's no real reason for it to be native. I don't need access to any of the phones hardware.
it sounds like a project where you would want a senior opinion on the architecture
which I would definitely do in Ionic-Cordova
mobile as well as native?

Try to ignore how humbling the video is in terms of our coding abilities and pay attention to the way the interviewee talks about Big O, Edge Cases, and questioning the premise of the question, e.g. "If it's 10 million integers long, can it still fit in memory?"

^I know some of these standards have ones because people haven’t submitted the project, but you don’t necessarily need help. Which of these standards would 3+ people like help with in the form of a breakout?

Here are the standards that have 50% or fewer 3s: 
```
-Deploy a fullstack single-page application	
-Refactor code to use encapsulation, polymorphism and inheritance	
-Explain the Big O of algorithms in the O(log n) and O(n log n) space	
-Solve problems that require memory references	
-Solve problems that require recursive iteration	
-Solve problems that require swapping	
-Build a CRUD app with a single resource in Java / PHP / Ruby / Python / Go	
-Build an Angular CRUD application against an HTTP API	
```

The STAR method for interviewing: <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Situation,_Task,_Action,_Result>

attachments.text:
The STAR (Situation, Task, Action, Result) format is a job interview technique used by interviewers to gather all the relevant information about a specific capability that the job requires. This interview format is said to have a higher degree of predictability of future on-the-job performance than the traditional interview. This technique is a behavioral interview technique.
Situation: The interviewer wants you to present a recent challenge and situation in which you found yourself.
Task: What did you have to achieve? The interviewer will be looking to see what you were trying to achieve from the situation. Some performance development methods use “Target” rather than “Task”. Job interview candidates who describe a “Target” they set themselves instead of an externally imposed “Task” emphasize their own intrinsic motivation to perform and to develop their performance.
Action: What did you do? The interviewer will be looking for information on what you did, why you did it and what the alternatives were.
Results: What was the outcome of your actions? What did you achieve through your actions and did you meet your objectives? What did you learn from this experience and have you used this learning since?
The STAR technique is similar to the SOARA technique.

attachments.title: Classes
attachments.text: JavaScript classes introduced in ECMAScript 2015 are syntactical sugar over JavaScript's existing prototype-based inheritance. The class syntax is not introducing a new object-oriented inheritance model to JavaScript. JavaScript classes provide a much simpler and clearer syntax to create objects and deal with inheritance.

messages.text: <http://sqlzoo.net/wiki/SQL_Tutorial>

How to install Postgres
Directions

Install Postgres:
$ brew install postgresql

Install Homebrew Services:
$ brew tap homebrew/services

Start Postgres as a service:
$ brew services start postgres

Bootstrap a database:
$ createdb

Verify that Postgres is running:
$ psql

If it worked, you'll see something like this:
psql (9.5.3)
Type "help" for help.

dannyfritz=#
Quit out of psql with \q:

psql (9.5.3)
Type "help" for help.

dannyfritz=# \q
$
Finished! :tada:

Congratulations! Now Postgres will automatically start automatically on login!

Bonus

See a list of all services running with:
$ brew services list

Stop Postgres from running with:
$ brew services stop postgres
BZ and I might be running late, bad bus traffic...
Once most of you have re-submitted your answers, I will release my solution.

## How was this graded?

Each question will map to one or more standards in the mastery tracker.
Each standard has multiple success criteria.
However a pop quiz question may only test one/some of the success criteria.
Each success criteria will be tested throughout the course.

What this means is:
* if you answer a pop quiz question correctly, your mastery goes UP for the
  standard(s) that that question is testing.
* if you answer a pop quiz question incorrectly, your mastery goes DOWN for the
  standard(s) that that question is testing.

To get your mastery back to 3, you need to demonstrate to an instructor that
you have mastered one or more of the success criteria for that standard.

<@U2UNJSF4H> The answer is “it depends”.  One needs to weigh the alternatives and pick the best one.  Space considerations like what Kyle is pointing out, would be a concern on a table that might grow really large (“really large” depends on the database and your DBA).  Complexity considerations (how your queries are impacted, whether you need to store that composite key in other places, whether using a surrogate key would speed up performance) should be thought about too.
<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/You_aren't_gonna_need_it>

attachments.text: "You aren't gonna need it" (acronym: YAGNI) is a principle of extreme programming (XP) that states a programmer should not add functionality until deemed necessary. XP co-founder Ron Jeffries has written: "Always implement things when you actually need them, never when you just foresee that you need them." Other forms of the phrase include "You aren't going to need it" and "You ain't gonna need it".

<!channel> *TLDR; you're about to receive an updated email requesting your signature, please give it a read and sign it* As we wrap 2016, we continue to be impressed and inspired by your commitment and accomplishments, and we are proud that Galvanize has played a role. We are also proud have launched The Galvanize Standard earlier this year, making our placement process and information even more transparent for both current and prospective students. To that end, we have an immediate ask/action-item of you (TLDR: a DocuSign will land in your inbox in the next 24 hours).

The United States Bureau of Labor Statistics publishes a list of Standard Occupational Classification (SOC) codes, categorizing all jobs for the purpose of collecting, calculating, or disseminating employment data. Moving forward, we will be disclosing all Standard Occupational Classification (SOC) codes that pertain to Galvanize programs - ensuring that we are supporting our student’s career transformation and being transparent regarding the roles for which the Galvanize programs prepare students. This is also compliant with the State of California’s Bureau for Private Postsecondary Education recently revised regulations (addendum with Codes attached), asking schools to communicate the explicit SOC codes applicable to their programs, and asking students to acknowledge receipt of these codes. We will be integrating the SOC codes into the Student Catalog for all current and incoming students, and you can expect to receive the addendum via Docusign in your inbox within the next 24 hours. 

By reviewing the SOC codes and signing this form, you ensure that Galvanize is able to responsibly collect, report, and communicate placement data. This information is critical for prospective students to accurately assess our program, and we thank you for your support! 

Please feel free to reach out to our Director of Career Services, Jessica Thrasher, at <mailto:jessica.thrasher@galvanize.com|jessica.thrasher@galvanize.com>, or me with any questions or concerns. 

Happy Holidays!

I also hear there are a bunch of people interested in various fighting games! I have also heard there has been an interest in hooking up some retro games! :nintendo: :sega: :sonic: :mushroom_mario:

messages.text: If any of you want to come visit Galvanize (Platte Campus) on Sunday, please let me know. We’re hosting the pre-work review session 10am -12noon in LowerLevel Classroom 3. Be sure to check your email for details.

<!channel> Hello, folks!  We are hosting a Learn to Code Meet Up at Platte on Tuesday November 15th from 6-8PM.  This is a great opportunity to get extra coding time/instruction (and free pizza).  I highly recommend it.
Join <#C1W3AEVS8|colorado_events> to learn about an upcoming Galvanize & The Integer Group Hackathon!

Did I introduce myself?  If not, Hi g41!  I’m one of your instructors!  I would say that I am your most important instructor, but that is just vanity, I’m sure that the other instructors may say differently.  :wink:  All in all, there will be 4 staff helping you out, of which Sarah and I are 2.

Hi g41! I can’t wait to meet you all next week! I will be the Web Development Resident for your group - which means I will be helping out in the classroom. Feel free to slack me questions if you have any.
These invites will set you up with github in our system and unlock all the amazingness….
